[1] China (Tibet)
Date: Sun 11 Mar 2007
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: India eNews (from correspondents in Beijing, China) [edited]
<http://www.indiaenews.com/asia/20070311/42403.htm>

Poultry from a market in Lhasa, the capital of southwest China's
Tibet Autonomous Region, were found infected with the bird flu virus,
China's ministry of agriculture reported on [Tue 6 Mar 2007].
According to the ministry's information office, the birds died on 1
Mar 2007, and tests for the H5 virus performed by the National Avian
Influenza Reference Laboratory were positive.
Specialists and officials are taking measures to control the virus
and prevent further infection in the area, presumably spread by birds
migrating from east Africa to west Asia.
The measures include closure of market, a cull of poultry in the
market, disinfecting the area, inspections of poultry markets, and
monitoring of wild birds to prevent the spread of avian influenza.
Earlier this month [March 2007], 3 wild birds and 2 poultry birds
tested positive for the H5 virus out of 325 poultry and 20 wild birds
tested in Fujian province (China), where a woman who contracted the
disease [February 2007], is in a critical condition, according to
authorities.
--
