[3] Afghanistan
Date: Sat 10 Mar 2007
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Pak Tribune [edited]
<http://paktribune.com/news/index.shtml?171464>

Afghanistan will cull poultry after 13 new cases of the deadly H5N1
strain of bird flu were discovered, including some in the capital, a
United Nations official said.
Assadullah Azhari, the United Nations Food and Agriculture
Organisation (UN FAO) spokesperson in Afghanistan, said the latest
outbreak comprised 6 cases of home-raised poultry in the eastern
province of Nangarhar, 4 in Kabul, and 3 in eastern Kunar province.
"We collected samples from these areas and all tested positive,"
Azhari said. He added the government had not said how many birds
would be culled. Quarantine and vaccination measures were also being
used.
The World Animal Health Organisation (OIE) had already confirmed 2
outbreaks of H5N1 each in flocks of backyard poultry in Nangarhar and
in turkeys in Kunar. The total number of cases discovered [so far]
this year [2007], is 17.
Last month [February 2007], Afghanistan banned poultry imports to
prevent the spread of the virus.
Last year [2006], the H5N1 strain was found in poultry in at least 4
Afghan provinces, leading to the killing of thousands of birds, but
there were no human deaths.
Afghanistan imports a large amount of poultry, mostly from Pakistan.
The ban imposed also applies to other countries affected by H5N1,
including Britain, Turkey and Indonesia.
The country [is located] at the junction of central and south Asia
and is on the migration route for several species of wild birds.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The outbreak in Tibet has been mentioned before but it appears as if
definitive information and critical details still have not been
submitted to OIE or formally disseminated in some other fashion.
While most of the cases have been in backyard poultry, flocks of a
couple thousand birds have been affected, as well as falcons in the
Kuwait Zoo. While the article indicates the number of cases is
waning, there is an ebb and flow to the spread, so far, in the
country and continued efforts to practice strict biosecurity and
intensive surveillance are still required.
The location of outbreaks in Afghanistan can be seen on the
administrative map at
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/afghanis-reg.pdf>
- Mod.PC]
